Video Games Data Analysis

Now you get to explore this exciting dataset! Cant think of where to start? Try your hand at these questions:

  • Games on what platform are the most popular?
  • What genre of games is the least popular in North America?
  • Are games that are popular in Japan also popular in Europe?
  • Plot the number sales of every publisher in function of time.

2. Loading and Preparing the Data

The data set comes from Kaggle and includes the number of sold copies in million for Videos Games from 1980 to 2020. For each Video Game we have also information about the Genre, the Publisher and the Platform as well as the rank regarding to the Global Sales. The Global Sales (in video games) is the sum of the sold video games from North America (NA_Sales), Europe (EU_Sales), Japan (JP_Sales) and others (Other_Sales). The data set contains 16,598 rows.

The description in a short overview:

variable description
Rank The rank of the video game, determined by global sales
Name The name of the video game
Platform The platform the video game was published on
Year The year the video game was published
Genre The genre of the video game
Publisher The publisher of the video game
NA_Sales The number of sales of the video game in North America
EU_Sales The number of sales of the video game in Europe
JP_Sales The number of sales of the video game in Japan
Other_Sales The number of sales of the video game in the rest of the world
Global_Sales The total number of sales of the video game

As the glimpse of data showed, we need to transform some of the data. We need Year as an integer, as well as Platform, Genre and Publisher as factor:

data$Year <- as.integer(data$Year)

data$Platform <- as.factor(data$Platform)
data$Genre <- as.factor(data$Genre)
data$Publisher <- as.factor(data$Publisher)

Now, we can see, that we have missing values for some years.

aggr(data)

Since the year is only missing for 1,5% of the data, we exclude those video games from the analysis.

data_clean <- data %>% drop_na()

3. Published Video Games per Year

The 70s and early 80s are known as the golden age of video gaming (game.de). What does this histogram show? The dataset lists each video game as one row, containing information like Platform, Publisher and Sales Data in different regions. So, the frequency per year refers to the number of video games published in that year.

Year_hist <- data_clean %>% ggplot(aes(x=Year)) +
  geom_bar()+
    ggtitle("Histogram of Video Games per Year") +
    ylab("Frequency")+
    xlab("Year")+
    theme_bw() + 
      theme(
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 9),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "white", size = 4, colour = "white"),
        axis.ticks = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
      )
Year_hist

The data starts right after that and the histogram shows a small drop in the frequency of sold video games with the early 80s. Until the mid 90s, the number of video games remains stable. \ With the Playstation 11994/95 the next big increase started. And from then, the number of video games per year increased from year to year. Until 2012. What happend 2012? Lets take a deeper look into the frequency per platforms.

Year_hist_Platform <- data_clean %>% ggplot(aes(x=Year)) +

4. Sales

We try to get an overview and group the data by Year. For each year, the sold video games, is the sum.

Sales_Year<-data_clean %>% group_by(Year) %>% summarise(Global_Sales_Year =sum(Global_Sales),Other_Sales_Year = sum(Other_Sales),
                                                        Japan_Sales_Year = sum(JP_Sales),
                                                        NorthAmerica_Sales_Year = sum(NA_Sales),
                                                        Europe_Sales_Year = sum(EU_Sales))
head(Sales_Year)
## # A tibble: 6  6
##    Year Global_Sales_Year Other_Sales_Year Japan_Sales_Year NorthAmerica_Sales_
##   <int>             <dbl>            <dbl>            <dbl>                <dbl>
## 1  1980              11.4             0.12              0                  10.6 
## 2  1981              35.8             0.32              0                  33.4 
## 3  1982              28.9             0.31              0                  26.9 
## 4  1983              16.8             0.14              8.1                 7.76
## 5  1984              50.4             0.7              14.3                33.3 
## 6  1985              53.9             0.92             14.6                33.7 
## #  with 1 more variable: Europe_Sales_Year <dbl>

With that, we get this graph with the years from 1980 to 2021 on the x-axis and the number of sold video games (in million) on the y-axis. For 2020 and 2021, the number of video games are not zero, but close.

SalesByYear<- Sales_Year %>% ggplot() +
    geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Year, y=Global_Sales_Year, col="Global")) +
    geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Year,y=Other_Sales_Year, col="Other"))+
    geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Year,y=Japan_Sales_Year, col="Japan"))+
    geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Year,y=NorthAmerica_Sales_Year, col="NorthAmerica"))+
    geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Year,y=Europe_Sales_Year, col="Europe"))+
    scale_color_manual(name="Region", values=c("Global"="deeppink3","Other"="coral2","Japan"="darkolivegreen",
                                "NorthAmerica"="darkcyan", "Europe"="darkseagreen"))+
   ggtitle("Sold Games by Region") +
    ylab("Sold Games (in million copies)")+
    theme_bw() + 
      theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
          axis.text = element_text(size = 9),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "white", size = 4, colour = "white"),
    #legend.justification = c(0, 1),
    legend.position = c(0.125, 0.75),
    axis.ticks = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
      )+
      transition_reveal(Year)
animate(SalesByYear, res = 69)
anim_save("SalesByYear.gif", animation = last_animation(), path = NULL)

4.1 Platforms by Regional Sales and Year

Next, we will take a deeper look into the different platforms. First, we transform the data to a long version. We add the column Sales_Region which is the amount of video games (in million) sold for the region specified in Sales_Type - the second column we added.

head(data_clean_long)
## # A tibble: 6  8
##    Rank Name              Platform  Year Genre Publisher Sales_Type Sales_Region
##   <dbl> <chr>             <fct>    <int> <fct> <fct>     <chr>             <dbl>
## 1     1 Wii Sports        Wii       2006 Spor Nintendo  Other_Sal         8.46
## 2     1 Wii Sports        Wii       2006 Spor Nintendo  JP_Sales           3.77
## 3     1 Wii Sports        Wii       2006 Spor Nintendo  NA_Sales          41.5 
## 4     1 Wii Sports        Wii       2006 Spor Nintendo  EU_Sales          29.0 
## 5     1 Wii Sports        Wii       2006 Spor Nintendo  Global_Sa        82.7 
## 6     2 Super Mario Bros. NES       1985 Plat Nintendo  Other_Sal         0.77

Now we can plot a bar chart with all Platforms including the different types of Sales (for each region). Since we do not want to look at one specific year, we plot all at ones.

PlatformByYear <- data_clean_long %>% filter(Sales_Type!="Global_Sales")  %>%
    ggplot(aes(fill=Sales_Type, x=Platform, y=Sales_Region))+
    geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity") + 
        ggtitle("Sales by Region and Platform") +
        ylab("Sales (in million copies) by Region")+
        xlab("Type of Platform")+
        coord_flip()+
    theme_bw() + 
      theme(
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 5),
        axis.ticks = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
          ) + facet_wrap(~ Year)
PlatformByYear
